\# Interview Notes

\## Interview Format

This document is written from an interview perspective. Questions are asked by the interviewer, and answers are given as though I am the candidate.

\---

\## 1. Core Java

\### Q: Explain the Java Memory Model (JMM).

A: The Java Memory Model defines how Java threads interact through shared memory and what behaviors are legal in a multithreaded environment. After 7 years working on highly concurrent systems, I rely on the JMM as the foundation for visibility and ordering guarantees. It distinguishes between main memory and thread-local caches, defines happens-before relationships, and explains how actions like reads, writes, lock acquire/release, volatile writes/reads, and final field initialization become visible across threads.

A strong understanding of JMM helps avoid subtle bugs such as stale reads, out-of-order execution, and broken double-checked locking. In production, I treat \`volatile\` or synchronization as the contract boundary for safe publication of shared state.

\### Q: How does \`volatile\` work?

A: \`volatile\` provides visibility and ordering guarantees without full mutual exclusion. A write to a volatile field establishes a happens-before relationship with subsequent reads of that field, so updates become visible to other threads immediately. It also prevents certain compiler and CPU reorderings around the volatile access.

I use \`volatile\` for state flags, completion markers, and simple one-writer/many-reader scenarios. I avoid it for compound operations because it does not make actions like \`count++\` atomic; in those cases I use \`AtomicInteger\`, \`synchronized\`, or \`ReentrantLock\`.

\### Q: \`synchronized\` vs \`ReentrantLock\`.

A: \`synchronized\` is simple, reliable, and the right choice for most critical sections. It is easier to reason about and automatically releases the lock when the block exits.

\`ReentrantLock\` is my choice when I need advanced behavior: timed lock acquisition with \`tryLock\`, interruptible lock acquisition, fairness policies, or multiple \`Condition\` objects. In a multithreaded batch processing service I used \`ReentrantLock\` to avoid deadlocks when threads needed to acquire locks in non-deterministic order and to implement a custom waiting queue.

\### Q: \`HashMap\` internal working in Java 8+.

A: Java 8+ \`HashMap\` uses an array of bins. Each bin starts as a linked list, and once the chain exceeds a threshold it converts to a balanced red-black tree to keep lookups near O(log n). On insert, the hash is spread to reduce collisions, the bucket index is computed, and existing keys are compared with \`equals()\`.

A \`HashMap\` resize copies entries to a larger array and redistributes them efficiently by reusing the old buckets’ low/high bits. In a past performance audit, I found a poorly chosen \`hashCode()\` caused excessive treeification and fixed it to restore consistent lookup times.

\### Q: \`ConcurrentHashMap\` internals.

A: \`ConcurrentHashMap\` is designed for high concurrency without global locking. It uses a combination of CAS-based updates, volatile reads, and limited synchronized blocks. In Java 8+, the structure is similar to \`HashMap\`, but bins are initialized lazily and multi-threaded updates are coordinated via CAS on the table array, with per-bin locks for treeification or complex modifications.

Read paths are mostly lock-free and can tolerate concurrent modifications. The size calculation uses optimistic reads and may require retries. In production, I use \`ConcurrentHashMap\` for caches and dispatch maps where low-latency access under contention is essential.

\### Q: \`equals()\` vs \`hashCode()\`.

A: \`equals()\` defines logical equality, and \`hashCode()\` defines the bucket placement in hash-based collections. The contract is strict: if two objects are equal, they must return the same hash code; if their hash codes differ, they cannot be equal.

With seven years of experience, I also emphasize that the hash code should be stable for the lifetime of the object while it is used as a map key. Mutable fields in \`hashCode()\` often cause hard-to-debug collection corruption.

\### Q: Why are Strings immutable?

A: Strings are immutable for a few practical reasons: security, thread safety, caching, and consistency. As a shared object used for keys, class names, and headers, immutability means I can safely share \`String\` instances across threads without locking.

It also enables JVM optimizations such as string interning and reuse of hash codes. In the JVM, immutable strings are the basis for safe publish patterns and for using string constants as map keys in shared caches.

\### Q: Difference between \`ArrayList\` and \`LinkedList\`.

A: \`ArrayList\` uses a contiguous array, making random access and iteration very fast. It is usually my default list implementation unless I need frequent insertions/removals in the middle of the list.

\`LinkedList\` is a doubly-linked structure with cheaper insert/remove in the middle but much higher memory overhead and slower traversal. In practice, I avoid \`LinkedList\` unless there is a strong requirement for queue-like operations or constant-time insertion at known positions.

\### Q: \`Comparable\` vs \`Comparator\`.

A: \`Comparable\` defines a natural ordering on the object itself through \`compareTo()\`. I use it when there is a default business ordering, such as by \`id\` or \`timestamp\`.

\`Comparator\` is external and more flexible. In senior work, I often rely on Java 8 \`Comparator.comparing()\`, reversing, and chaining comparators for dynamic sort criteria and for sorting objects by different attributes without changing the class.

\### Q: Explain Garbage Collection and G1GC.

A: Garbage collection reclaims memory by identifying objects that are no longer reachable. In JVM production services, I tune GC as part of performance engineering.

G1GC is a server-style collector that partitions the heap into regions and performs concurrent marking with incremental evacuation. It targets predictable pauses by collecting the youngest regions first and then mixing old regions as needed. I have used G1 on services with large heaps to reduce full GC pauses and to meet strict latency SLAs.

\### Q: How does \`CompletableFuture\` work?

A: \`CompletableFuture\` is an asynchronous computation primitive that supports chaining, composition, and non-blocking event-driven programming. You can start tasks with \`supplyAsync()\`, chain dependent tasks with \`thenApply()\`, combine multiple futures with \`allOf()\`/\`anyOf()\`, and handle exceptions with \`handle\`, \`exceptionally\`, or \`whenComplete\`.

In a microservice I used \`CompletableFuture\` to parallelize remote service calls, collect results, and fall back gracefully when one of the calls timed out.

\### Q: Producer-Consumer implementation.

A: I prefer \`BlockingQueue\` implementations such as \`ArrayBlockingQueue\` or \`LinkedBlockingQueue\` for clean producer-consumer coordination. Producers call \`put()\` and consumers call \`take()\`, and the queue itself handles blocking, backpressure, and thread safety.

In a real system, I also add a poison pill or shutdown signal, and I manage thread pool sizes carefully to avoid resource starvation.

\### Q: Functional interfaces and Stream API.

A: Functional interfaces, like \`Function\`, \`Predicate\`, and \`Consumer\`, are the basis for lambdas and method references. Streams let me transform and reduce collections declaratively with pipeline operations such as \`filter\`, \`map\`, \`flatMap\`, \`collect\`, and \`reduce\`.

With experience, I use streams for expressive data processing while staying mindful of not overusing them in performance-sensitive hot paths.

\### Q: Find duplicate elements using Streams.

A: I typically use grouping and counting or track seen elements in a set:

\`\`\`java

List duplicates = list.stream()

.collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Function.identity(), Collectors.counting()))

.entrySet().stream()

.filter(e -> e.getValue() > 1)

.map(Map.Entry::getKey)

.collect(Collectors.toList());

\`\`\`

For large data sets, I prefer a set-based approach to reduce memory overhead.

\### Q: Find second highest salary using Streams.

A: One robust approach is:

\`\`\`java

int secondHighest = employees.stream()

.map(Employee::getSalary)

.distinct()

.sorted(Comparator.reverseOrder())

.skip(1)

.findFirst()

.orElseThrow(() -> new NoSuchElementException("No second highest salary"));

\`\`\`

When working with very large data sets, I push these calculations into the database instead of bringing all rows into Java.

