\## 2. Spring Boot

\### Q: How does Spring Boot start internally?

A: Spring Boot startup begins with \`SpringApplication.run()\`. It loads configuration through \`SpringFactoriesLoader\`, builds the \`Environment\`, creates the \`ApplicationContext\`, performs component scanning, loads auto-configuration classes annotated with \`@Configuration\` and \`@EnableAutoConfiguration\`, and registers beans.

During startup it also applies \`ApplicationContextInitializer\`s, refreshes the context, and triggers \`ApplicationRunner\` and \`CommandLineRunner\` beans. For web applications, it bootstraps an embedded servlet container like Tomcat or Jetty.

\### Q: Explain Spring Bean lifecycle.

A: The lifecycle starts with bean instantiation, dependency injection, \`BeanNameAware\`/\`BeanFactoryAware\` callbacks, \`BeanPostProcessor\` pre-processing, \`@PostConstruct\` or \`afterPropertiesSet()\`, and finally \`BeanPostProcessor\` post-processing. For singleton beans, the lifecycle ends with destruction callbacks such as \`@PreDestroy\` or \`DisposableBean.destroy()\` when the context closes.

As a senior engineer, I also use \`SmartInitializingSingleton\` and custom post-processors to plug cross-cutting behavior into lifecycle events.

\### Q: Singleton bean thread safety.

A: Singleton beans are shared across threads, so thread safety depends on whether the bean maintains mutable state. I treat singleton services as stateless by default; if state is required, I use thread-safe structures, immutability, or properly scoped beans.

For example, a cache service may use \`ConcurrentHashMap\`, while request-scoped data stays in \`ThreadLocal\` or request-scoped beans.

\### Q: Difference between \`@Component\`, \`@Service\`, and \`@Repository\`.

A: All three are Spring stereotypes that register a bean in the context. \`@Component\` is generic, \`@Service\` signals a service layer component, and \`@Repository\` signals data access and enables persistence exception translation.

I use the specific stereotypes for semantic clarity and to follow layering conventions in enterprise applications.

\### Q: Constructor vs Field Injection.

A: Constructor injection is my preferred pattern because it makes dependencies explicit, supports immutability, enables easier unit testing, and prevents partially initialized beans. Field injection hides dependencies and makes a class harder to use outside Spring.

In a large codebase, constructor injection also helps catch missing dependencies at compile time.

\### Q: How does \`@Transactional\` work?

A: \`@Transactional\` is implemented via AOP proxies that wrap a method call. The proxy starts a transaction before invoking the target method and commits or rolls back afterward depending on the outcome and the rollback rules.

I am careful with self-invocation because internal calls bypass the proxy. In production code, I isolate transactional boundaries in public service methods and keep transactional methods small and well-scoped.

\### Q: Propagation levels.

A: I use propagation levels to control whether a method participates in an existing transaction or starts a new one. Common levels are:

\- \`REQUIRED\`: join existing or create new

\- \`REQUIRES\_NEW\`: suspend existing and create a new transaction

\- \`SUPPORTS\`: join if present, otherwise run non-transactionally

\- \`NOT\_SUPPORTED\`: execute outside any transaction

\- \`MANDATORY\`: require an existing transaction

\- \`NESTED\`: create a nested savepoint-based transaction within a larger one

I typically use \`REQUIRED\`, and I choose \`REQUIRES\_NEW\` for audit/logging or compensation actions that must commit independently.

\### Q: Isolation levels.

A: Isolation controls concurrent visibility. In Spring, common levels map to database behavior:

\- \`READ\_UNCOMMITTED\`: dirty reads allowed

\- \`READ\_COMMITTED\`: no dirty reads

\- \`REPEATABLE\_READ\`: stable repeated reads, still possible phantom reads depending on DB

\- \`SERIALIZABLE\`: full isolation, highest contention

I use \`READ\_COMMITTED\` as a sensible default and raise isolation only when business correctness demands it.

\### Q: Lazy vs Eager loading.

A: Eager loading fetches associated entities immediately, while lazy loading defers fetch until the association is accessed. I default to \`FetchType.LAZY\` for collections and many-to-one relationships, because eager fetching can cause large joins and unnecessary memory pressure.

To avoid LazyInitializationException, I either open a transaction around the view, use DTO projections, or explicitly initialize associations with fetch joins.

\### Q: Solve the N+1 query problem.

A: I identify N+1 with query logging and performance tools, then refactor the data access layer. Common fixes are \`JOIN FETCH\`, entity graphs, or batch fetching.

In one project, I replaced repeated lazy loads in a list rendering flow with a single optimized query and reduced database round trips by 90%.

\### Q: Spring Security authentication flow.

A: Spring Security uses a chain of servlet filters. Credentials are extracted by an authentication filter, turned into an \`Authentication\` token, and passed to the \`AuthenticationManager\`. The manager delegates to configured \`AuthenticationProvider\`s.

On success, the \`SecurityContextHolder\` stores the \`Authentication\`. Authorization is then performed by access decision voters or method security interceptors based on roles and authorities.

\### Q: JWT implementation.

A: I implement JWT by issuing a signed token after authentication, including standard claims such as subject, issuer, expiry, and optionally custom claims. The token is returned to the client and validated on each request via a filter.

I also design refresh tokens for long-lived sessions, rotate secrets when necessary, and mitigate replay attacks by storing token identifiers or using short expiration windows.

\### Q: Exception handling using \`@ControllerAdvice\`.

A: \`@ControllerAdvice\` centralizes exception mapping across controllers. I map application exceptions to structured error responses and standard HTTP statuses, often producing a uniform payload with \`errorCode\`, \`message\`, and \`timestamp\`.

This keeps controllers clean and provides consistent client behavior.

\### Q: Validation using Bean Validation.

A: I use Hibernate Validator annotations like \`@NotNull\`, \`@Size\`, \`@Email\`, and custom constraint validators. I validate request payloads with \`@Valid\` and handle violations centrally, returning meaningful validation errors to API clients.

In complex forms, I also use validation groups for scenario-specific rules.

