\## 4. SQL

\### Q: Second highest salary.

A: A robust SQL solution is:

\`\`\`sql

SELECT salary

FROM (

SELECT salary,

DENSE\_RANK() OVER (ORDER BY salary DESC) AS rank

FROM employees

) t

WHERE rank = 2;

\`\`\`

In systems with large tables, I also consider performance and use indexes on salary.

\### Q: Department-wise highest salary.

A: I typically write:

\`\`\`sql

SELECT department\_id,

MAX(salary) AS highest\_salary

FROM employees

GROUP BY department\_id;

\`\`\`

For additional detail, I join back to the employee table if I need the employee record as well.

\### Q: Difference between \`ROW\_NUMBER()\`, \`RANK()\`, and \`DENSE\_RANK()\`.

A: \`ROW\_NUMBER()\` assigns a unique sequential number to each row. \`RANK()\` assigns the same rank to ties and leaves gaps afterward. \`DENSE\_RANK()\` assigns the same rank to ties but does not leave gaps.

I choose the function based on whether gaps are acceptable in ranking results.

\### Q: Index types.

A: Important index types are B-tree indexes for general lookup and range scans, hash indexes for exact match lookups, unique indexes, composite indexes, partial/index-filtered indexes, and full-text indexes.

In production databases, I also consider covering indexes to reduce lookups and index-only scans.

\### Q: Clustered vs Non-clustered index.

A: A clustered index defines the physical order of rows in the table. A non-clustered index stores pointers to the data rows and can be created on additional columns.

Because there is usually one clustered index per table, I choose it carefully for the most common range or ordering queries.

\### Q: Composite index.

A: Composite indexes include multiple columns and are most effective when queries filter or sort by the leftmost columns. I avoid redundant composite indexes and rely on index selectivity when designing them.

\### Q: Explain query execution.

A: Query execution starts with parsing, then semantic analysis, optimization, and plan generation. The optimizer chooses join orders, access methods, and whether to use indexes. The execution engine then reads data, joins rows, and returns results.

I use execution plans and statistics to diagnose performance issues.

\### Q: ACID properties.

A: ACID stands for Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, and Durability. It guarantees that transactions are all-or-nothing, keep the database in a valid state, isolate concurrent transactions, and persist committed changes.

In distributed systems, I map these guarantees carefully to business requirements and often relax strict consistency in favor of availability.

\### Q: Deadlock.

A: Deadlocks occur when transactions hold locks the others need and form a circular wait. I troubleshoot them by analyzing lock wait graphs and by enforcing consistent lock order, keeping transactions short, and using lower isolation levels when appropriate.

Many DBMSes detect deadlocks automatically and abort one transaction; in the application I handle retries for that case.

\### Q: Optimizing slow queries.

A: I optimize queries by reviewing execution plans, checking missing or unused indexes, rewriting slow joins, avoiding functions in predicates, and reducing data volume with projections and filters.

I also evaluate whether the logic belongs in the database or the application layer, and sometimes introduce caching for repeated expensive queries.

