\## 6. REST API

\### Q: REST principles.

A: REST principles include statelessness, resource-based endpoints, uniform use of HTTP verbs, meaningful URIs, and hypermedia when appropriate. I build APIs around resources and use standard response codes to make contracts predictable.

\### Q: PUT vs PATCH.

A: \`PUT\` performs a complete replacement of the resource, while \`PATCH\` applies a partial update. \`PUT\` is idempotent, and \`PATCH\` is used when only a subset of fields need changing.

\### Q: POST idempotency.

A: \`POST\` is not inherently idempotent, but I make it idempotent by using client-generated request IDs or deduplication tokens for create operations.

This avoids duplicate side effects when clients retry due to network issues.

\### Q: API versioning.

A: I version APIs with URI paths (\`/v1/orders\`) for clarity and compatibility. I also use headers or content negotiation for advanced versioning schemes when needed.

The goal is to evolve without breaking existing clients.

\### Q: Pagination.

A: I implement pagination with limit/offset for simple use cases and cursor/keyset pagination for larger or ordered data sets. Cursor-based pagination is more efficient and avoids inconsistent results from inserts or deletes during traversal.

\### Q: HATEOAS.

A: HATEOAS adds hypermedia links to responses so clients can discover available actions. I use it in APIs where the client benefits from navigation hints and state transitions.

\### Q: HTTP status codes.

A: I use 2xx for successful responses, 4xx for client errors, and 5xx for server errors. Common mappings are 200 OK, 201 Created, 204 No Content, 400 Bad Request, 401 Unauthorized, 403 Forbidden, 404 Not Found, 409 Conflict, and 500 Internal Server Error.

\### Q: Authentication vs Authorization.

A: Authentication verifies who the request is from. Authorization decides what that authenticated user is allowed to do. Both are separate concerns in secure API design.

