\## 7. Cloud & DevOps

\### Q: Docker lifecycle.

A: Docker lifecycle includes authoring a Dockerfile, building an image, running a container, monitoring its health, and cleaning up unused images and containers. I also use multi-stage builds to keep images small and secure.

\### Q: Kubernetes Pods and Deployments.

A: A Pod is the smallest deployable unit and can contain one or more containers. A Deployment manages replica sets, rolling updates, and declarative scaling for Pods.

\### Q: CI/CD pipeline.

A: A CI/CD pipeline automates building, testing, and deploying code. Good pipelines include linting, unit tests, integration tests, security scans, and staged deployments to environments such as staging and production.

\### Q: Health checks.

A: Health checks verify that a service is functioning. Liveness checks ensure the container is alive, while readiness checks ensure the service is ready to accept traffic.

\### Q: Readiness vs Liveness probes.

A: Liveness probes restart unhealthy containers. Readiness probes keep a container out of service until it is ready.

\### Q: Environment configuration.

A: I externalize configuration using environment variables, config maps, or config servers. This separates code from configuration and supports multiple deployment environments.

\### Q: Secrets management.

A: I store secrets in dedicated tools like Vault, AWS Secrets Manager, or Kubernetes Secrets, and I avoid embedding them in images or source control.

\### Q: Logging in production.

A: Production logging should be centralized, structured, and correlated with request or trace IDs. I set log levels carefully and ensure logs are retained and searchable for troubleshooting.

