\## 9. Coding Questions

\### Q: Longest substring without repeating characters.

A: I solve it with a sliding window and a last-seen index map. This is O(n) time and is robust for long strings.

\### Q: LRU Cache.

A: I implement an LRU cache with \`LinkedHashMap\` or a custom combination of a doubly-linked list and hashmap, providing O(1) get/put operations and deterministic eviction.

\### Q: Merge intervals.

A: I sort intervals by start time and merge overlapping ranges in one pass. This is effective for scheduling, calendar, and resource allocation problems.

\### Q: Reverse linked list.

A: I reverse a linked list iteratively with \`prev\`, \`current\`, and \`next\` pointers to avoid recursion overhead.

\### Q: Detect cycle in linked list.

A: I use Floyd’s cycle-finding algorithm with slow and fast pointers. If they meet, there is a cycle.

\### Q: Binary search variations.

A: I implement standard binary search and variants for lower/upper bound, first/last occurrence, and rotated arrays. I also handle edge cases carefully to avoid infinite loops.

\### Q: Top K frequent elements.

A: I count frequencies in a map and use a min-heap or bucket sort to extract the top K. For large streams, I consider approximate algorithms if exact ranking is too expensive.

\### Q: Producer-Consumer implementation.

A: I implement it using \`BlockingQueue\` and thread pools, with proper shutdown coordination and optional backpressure when producers outpace consumers.

\### Q: Implement custom cache.

A: I build custom caches with eviction policies like LRU, TTL, or size-based eviction, using a hashmap for lookup and a linked structure to maintain eviction order.

